##Sonatype Nexus OSS (Open Source Edition) is a 
universal artifact repository manager used to store, 
manage, and distribute software components such as 
Maven libraries, Docker images, npm packages, and more. 
It acts as a central hub for all build artifacts in DevOps pipelines.

    Integrates with CI/CD tools
        Nexus integrates smoothly with:
        • Jenkins
        • GitHub Actions
        • GitLab CI
        • Azure DevOps
        CI pipelines can pull dependencies and push build artifacts to Nexus.


        Types of Repositories in Nexus OSS
            Nexus supports three main repository types:

        • Hosted → Store your internal artifacts
        • Proxy → Cache external repositories
        • Group → Combine multiple repos under one URL
        This structure simplifies dependency management across projects.



## SonarQube is a code quality and security platform, 
while the SonarQube Scanner is the tool 
that performs the actual code analysis and sends results to 
the SonarQube server. They are different components but work together.

    What SonarQube Is Used For
        SonarQube is a centralized platform that continuously inspects code for:
        • Bugs
        • Code smells
        • Security vulnerabilities
        • Duplications
        • Test coverage
        • Maintainability issues
        It provides a dashboard where developers, DevOps engineers, and architects can track code health over time.

    🧩 What the SonarQube Scanner Does
        The Scanner is the component that actually analyzes your source code. It runs locally or inside CI pipelines and sends the analysis report to the SonarQube server.
            According to SonarSource:
            • SonarQube = server that stores and displays results
            • SonarScanner = tool that performs analysis and uploads results



